---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const pageTitle = "About Ear Wax - Understanding Cerumen | Earwax Clinic Network";
const pageDescription = "Learn about ear wax (cerumen), why it builds up, symptoms of blockage, and when to seek professional help. Expert information from qualified ear care specialists.";
---

<BaseLayout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <main>
    <div class="hero-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h1>About Ear Wax (Cerumen)</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Understanding the natural process of ear wax production and when professional removal is needed for your ear health and comfort.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container">
      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>What is Ear Wax?</h2>
        <p>
          Ear wax, medically known as cerumen, is a natural waxy substance produced by the ear canal. It's created by specialized glands in the outer third of your ear canal and serves several important protective functions for your ears.
        </p>

        <div class="info-grid">
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>Natural Protection</h3>
            <p>Ear wax acts as a natural barrier, protecting your ear canal from dust, debris, and harmful bacteria that could cause infections.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>Self-Cleaning System</h3>
            <p>Your ears have a remarkable self-cleaning mechanism where old wax naturally migrates outward, carrying trapped particles with it.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>Moisture Control</h3>
            <p>Cerumen helps maintain the right moisture level in your ear canal, preventing dryness and irritation of the delicate skin.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Types of Ear Wax</h3>
        <p>There are two main types of ear wax, determined by genetics:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Wet Wax (Golden-brown):</strong> More common in Caucasian and African populations, stickier and darker in color</li>
          <li><strong>Dry Wax (Grey-white):</strong> More common in Asian and Native American populations, flakier and lighter in color</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Why Does Ear Wax Build Up?</h2>
        <p>
          While ear wax production is normal and healthy, several factors can cause it to accumulate and create blockages:
        </p>

        <div class="causes-list">
          <div class="cause-item">
            <h4>Overproduction</h4>
            <p>Some people naturally produce more wax than others due to genetic factors, age, or underlying skin conditions like eczema.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cause-item">
            <h4>Narrow Ear Canals</h4>
            <p>Individuals with naturally narrow or unusually shaped ear canals may experience more frequent blockages as wax has less space to migrate naturally.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cause-item">
            <h4>Hearing Aids & Earplugs</h4>
            <p>Regular use of hearing aids, earplugs, or earbuds can push wax deeper into the canal and prevent its natural outward migration.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cause-item">
            <h4>Cotton Bud Use</h4>
            <p>Using cotton buds or other objects to clean ears often pushes wax deeper, compacting it against the eardrum and causing blockages.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cause-item">
            <h4>Age-Related Changes</h4>
            <p>As we age, ear wax becomes drier and harder, making it more difficult for the ear's natural cleaning process to work effectively.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cause-item">
            <h4>Excessive Hair Growth</h4>
            <p>Increased hair growth in the ear canal, particularly common in older adults, can trap wax and prevent its natural removal.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Symptoms of Ear Wax Blockage</h2>
        <p>
          Recognizing the signs of ear wax impaction is important for knowing when to seek professional help. Common symptoms include:
        </p>

        <div class="symptoms-grid">
          <div class="symptom-category">
            <h3>Hearing Symptoms</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Reduced hearing or muffled sounds</li>
              <li>Feeling of fullness in the ear</li>
              <li>Hearing your own voice differently (autophony)</li>
              <li>Difficulty hearing in noisy environments</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="symptom-category">
            <h3>Physical Symptoms</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Ear pain or discomfort</li>
              <li>Itching in the ear canal</li>
              <li>Discharge from the ear</li>
              <li>Odor from the affected ear</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="symptom-category">
            <h3>Balance Symptoms</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Dizziness or vertigo</li>
              <li>Balance problems</li>
              <li>Nausea (in severe cases)</li>
              <li>Tinnitus (ringing in the ears)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <h4>⚠️ Important Warning Signs</h4>
          <p>Seek immediate medical attention if you experience:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Severe ear pain</li>
            <li>Sudden hearing loss</li>
            <li>Discharge that is bloody or has a foul smell</li>
            <li>Signs of infection (fever, severe pain, swelling)</li>
            <li>Dizziness with nausea and vomiting</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>When to Seek Professional Help</h2>
        <p>
          While some ear wax is normal and healthy, there are clear indicators when professional removal is necessary:
        </p>

        <div class="help-indicators">
          <div class="indicator-section">
            <h3>Immediate Professional Help Needed</h3>
            <ul class="priority-high">
              <li>Complete hearing loss in one or both ears</li>
              <li>Severe pain that doesn't improve</li>
              <li>Signs of infection (fever, pus, severe swelling)</li>
              <li>Dizziness affecting daily activities</li>
              <li>Tinnitus that's getting worse</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="indicator-section">
            <h3>Schedule an Appointment Soon</h3>
            <ul class="priority-medium">
              <li>Hearing has been reduced for more than a few days</li>
              <li>Home remedies haven't worked after a week</li>
              <li>Persistent feeling of fullness</li>
              <li>Itching or discomfort affecting daily life</li>
              <li>You wear hearing aids that aren't fitting properly</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="indicator-section">
            <h3>Consider Professional Cleaning If</h3>
            <ul class="priority-low">
              <li>You have a history of excessive wax buildup</li>
              <li>You work in dusty environments</li>
              <li>You regularly use earplugs or hearing aids</li>
              <li>You want professional ear health maintenance</li>
              <li>Over-the-counter drops cause irritation</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Professional vs. Home Treatment</h2>
        <div class="comparison-table">
          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Aspect</th>
                  <th>Professional Treatment</th>
                  <th>Home Treatment</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Safety</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ Performed by trained professionals</td>
                  <td>⚠️ Risk of pushing wax deeper</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Effectiveness</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ Complete removal guaranteed</td>
                  <td>⚠️ May only partially remove blockage</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Speed</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ Immediate results (20-30 minutes)</td>
                  <td>⚠️ May take days or weeks</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Cost</strong></td>
                  <td>⚠️ £65-95 per session</td>
                  <td>✅ £5-15 for drops/kits</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Comfort</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ Painless with proper technique</td>
                  <td>⚠️ May cause discomfort or irritation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Suitable For</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ Everyone, including those with ear problems</td>
                  <td>⚠️ Only for healthy ears</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cta-section">
        <div class="cta-content">
          <h2>Need Professional Ear Wax Removal?</h2>
          <p>Our qualified practitioners provide safe, effective ear wax removal using the latest microsuction and irrigation techniques.</p>
          <div class="cta-buttons">
            <a href="/earwax-clinic-locations/" class="btn btn-primary">Find Your Local Clinic</a>
            <a href="tel:08003317002" class="btn btn-secondary">Call 0800 331 7002</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .hero-section {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--primary-color) 0%, var(--secondary-color) 100%);
    color: white;
    padding: var(--spacing-4xl) 0 var(--spacing-3xl);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .hero-section h1 {
    color: white;
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-lg);
  }

  .content-section {
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-4xl);
    padding-top: var(--spacing-2xl);
  }

  .info-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--spacing-xl);
    margin: var(--spacing-2xl) 0;
  }

  .info-card {
    background: var(--background-light);
    padding: var(--spacing-xl);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color);
  }

  .info-card h3 {
    color: var(--primary-color);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
  }

  .causes-list {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(350px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--spacing-lg);
    margin: var(--spacing-xl) 0;
  }

  .cause-item {
    background: white;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--spacing-lg);
    transition: box-shadow var(--transition-normal);
  }

  .cause-item:hover {
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
  }

  .cause-item h4 {
    color: var(--secondary-color);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-sm);
  }

  .symptoms-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--spacing-xl);
    margin: var(--spacing-2xl) 0;
  }

  .symptom-category {
    background: var(--background-light);
    padding: var(--spacing-xl);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
  }

  .symptom-category h3 {
    color: var(--primary-color);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
  }

  .symptom-category ul {
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: var(--spacing-lg);
  }

  .warning-box {
    background: #FFF3CD;
    border: 1px solid #FFEAA7;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--spacing-xl);
    margin: var(--spacing-xl) 0;
  }

  .warning-box h4 {
    color: #B7791F;
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
  }

  .help-indicators {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(350px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--spacing-xl);
    margin: var(--spacing-2xl) 0;
  }

  .indicator-section {
    background: white;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--spacing-xl);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
  }

  .priority-high {
    color: #D32F2F;
  }

  .priority-medium {
    color: #F57C00;
  }

  .priority-low {
    color: var(--text-dark);
  }

  .comparison-table {
    margin: var(--spacing-2xl) 0;
  }

  .table-responsive {
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    background: white;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    overflow: hidden;
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
  }

  th, td {
    padding: var(--spacing-md) var(--spacing-lg);
    text-align: left;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  th {
    background: var(--primary-color);
    color: white;
    font-weight: var(--font-weight-semibold);
  }

  tr:hover {
    background: var(--background-light);
  }

  .cta-section {
    background: var(--background-light);
    padding: var(--spacing-4xl);
    border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
    text-align: center;
    margin: var(--spacing-4xl) 0;
  }

  .cta-content h2 {
    color: var(--primary-color);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-lg);
  }

  .cta-buttons {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--spacing-lg);
    justify-content: center;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: var(--spacing-xl);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .info-grid,
    .causes-list,
    .symptoms-grid,
    .help-indicators {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .cta-buttons {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
    }
  }
</style>